---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import LxvInteractivePreview from "../../components/LxvInteractivePreview";
---

<BaseLayout
    title="LXv Launch | Iordanis Antypas"
    description="Modular ROS2 Jazzy launch baseline for running experiments on the Franka FR3"
>
    <article class="mx-auto w-full max-w-4xl space-y-14 py-12">
        <header class="space-y-5">
            <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.12em] text-slate-400">Project</p>
            <h1 class="text-4xl font-semibold text-slate-100 md:text-5xl">LXv Launch</h1>
            <p class="text-lg text-slate-300">
                Modular ROS2 Jazzy launch baseline for running experiments on the Franka FR3.
            </p>
            <p class="max-w-3xl text-base leading-7 text-slate-300">
                A practical repository used in our lab for robot bring-up, controller management and small
                task-level experiments. Designed to be easy to run, modify and extend.
            </p>
            <figure class="space-y-2 pt-2">
                <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-slate-700/70 bg-slate-900/60">
                    <video
                        controls
                        preload="metadata"
                        class="aspect-video w-full"
                        poster="/favicon.svg"
                    >
                        <source src="/media/lxv-launch-hero.mp4" type="video/mp4" />
                        Your browser does not support the video tag.
                    </video>
                </div>
                <figcaption class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                    Real hardware execution using the LXv launch stack and example pouring task.
                </figcaption>
            </figure>
        </header>

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-100">What this repository is</h2>
            <p class="leading-7 text-slate-300">
                LXv Launch is a clean ROS2 launch and configuration baseline used in our lab for experiments
                with the Franka FR3.
            </p>
            <p class="leading-7 text-slate-300">It provides a structured starting point for:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300">
                <li>bringing up the robot</li>
                <li>spawning and switching controllers</li>
                <li>running simple task pipelines</li>
                <li>connecting lightweight UIs or teleoperation nodes</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="leading-7 text-slate-300">
                The focus is clarity and usability rather than completeness. It is intended to be easy to
                read and modify depending on the experiment.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-100">What you get</h2>
            <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300">
                <li>FR3 bring-up with ROS2 Jazzy</li>
                <li>Controller manager configuration</li>
                <li>Joint trajectory controller setup</li>
                <li>Basic servo / motion testing</li>
                <li>RViz + MoveIt visualization</li>
                <li>Example task pipeline (pouring demo)</li>
                <li>Simple UI connection example</li>
                <li>Modular launch structure for extension</li>
            </ul>
            <blockquote class="rounded-lg border-l-4 border-slate-500/80 bg-slate-900/40 px-4 py-3 text-slate-300">
                Real hardware is the primary target. Simulation support for Gazebo is added but is not the main
                focus.
            </blockquote>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-100">Interactive preview</h2>
            <p class="leading-7 text-slate-300">
                A lightweight browser model is included below to visualize the basic structure and example
                motion used in the demo. The specific semantics can be left up to interpertation but the essence is that the examples support both pre-planned motion or manual control, with modular augmentations easily made on top of the examples.
            </p>
            <p class="leading-7 text-slate-300">
                This is only a visual preview and is not connected to hardware.
            </p>
            <LxvInteractivePreview client:only="react" />
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-4">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-100">Who this may be useful for</h2>
            <p class="leading-7 text-slate-300">This repository may be useful if you:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-slate-300">
                <li>are starting work with FR3 + ROS2</li>
                <li>want a clean launch baseline</li>
                <li>need quick bring-up for experiments</li>
                <li>prefer modifying an existing structure instead of building from scratch</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="space-y-3 pb-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-100">Repository</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-300">
                GitHub:
                <a
                    href="https://github.com/jadipas/lxv_launch"
                    class="text-cyan-300 underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-cyan-200"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noreferrer"
                >
                    https://github.com/jadipas/lxv_launch
                </a>
            </p>
            <p class="text-slate-300">Documentation and setup instructions are available in the repository.</p>
        </section>
    </article>
</BaseLayout>
